1.Introduction¶

The design of high-performance antennas has become more demanding with the development of high frequency communication systems like 5G technology. In these high frequency systems, there are some standards that the antennas have to satisfy to perform effective signal transmission and reception across specified frequency intervals. During the design phase, the prediction of antenna characteristics and its performance using traditional electromagnetic simulations is computationally intensive. Therefore, it is difficult to conduct trial and error procedure to find out whether the antenna would meet the requirements. As an alternative way, the machine learning methods are intended to be used in this study to make inferences about the relation between the design parameters and the S11 parameter over multiple frequencies which is the measure of reflection.

2.Methodologies¶

To reveal the relation between the design parameters and the S11 parameter (return loss), the design parameters and their ranges given in Table 1 (in the homework pdf file) are used for sampling. In other words, some sample geometries which are in accordance with the given ranges are generated randomly and their performances are obtained with the help of an electromagnetic solver (simulation). The simulations are conducted within the frequency band of 23-33 GHz. After obtaining the sample antenna performances as output, the input dataset including the design/geometry parameters and the output dataset are analyzed using the dimensionality reduction and supervised learning techniques. More specifically, principal component analysis (PCA) and linear regression method are employed as the main methodologies in this study. PCA is particularly applied to the input dataset to reduce the complexity of the design space and more details about the dimensionality reduction with the PCA is discussed in Section 3.1. On the other hand, linear regression models are introduced to examine how the design parameters affect the S11 parameter and to predict the antenna performance based on the given design parameters. The work related to linear regression method is discussed detailly in Section 3.2. The aim of applying these methods is to detect the key parameters and clarify the relationship between the antenna's design parameters and its electromagnetic performance, as represented by the S11 parameter. Additionally, the performance of these methods is evaluated and the interpretation of the results is provided in Section 3.3.

Data¶

As it is mentioned previously, the data used in this homework is obtained through the simulation. The data has 385 designs/samples of geometries and these sample geometries include 11 design parameters, or in other words, features. The features are patch length, patch width, probe radius, metal thickness, substrate thickness, solder resist thickness, pad-probe radius difference, patch length ratio, substrate dielectric constant and solder resist dielectric constant. Shortly, the input data is the 385x11 data matrix which includes the design parameter values for corresponding samples. On the output side, there are 2 data matrices which indicates the S parameter value of the each sample for the 201 frequency points. More clearly, the output data consists of two 385x201 data matrices in which each column represents the return loss calculated at a specific frequency point. In total, there are 201 different frequency points. With two matrices, one of the data matrices represents the real part of the S11 parameter and the other one represents the imaginary part of the S11 parameter.

3.1 - Dimension Reduction with PCA¶

In order to apply the PCA to input data, firstly, the data is needed to be standardized. It is because the range of features differ, they are in different scales and the features with large variances would affect the principal components more. After the input data is standardized, the PCA is applied to the standardized data.

#Apply PCA to the standardized input data
pca = PCA()
pca_feature = pca.fit(input_data_std)
explained_variance = pca_feature.explained_variance_ratio_
cumulative_explained_variance = explained_variance.cumsum()
variance_data = [explained_variance,cumulative_explained_variance]
components = pca.components_
loadings = pd.DataFrame(components, columns=input_data_std.columns, index=[f'principal component {i+1}' for i in range(len(components))])
loadings_transposed = loadings.T
explained_variance_df = pd.DataFrame(variance_data, columns = [f'principal component {i+1}' for i in range(len(components))],index=["Explained Variance Ratio", "Cumulative Explained Variance Ratio"])
#Display the loadings

The selection of principal components can be stoppped once 80-90% of the total variance is explained. Based on this rule, the first 8 principal components seems to be favorable for explaining most of the total variance. By applying PCA to the input data, the effective geometric parameters/features can be identified and the dimensionality can be reduced from 11 features to 8 features while preserving most of the variance information. In other words, the design space can be simplified. Numerically, 86% of the total variance is captured with 8 principal components.

Besides that, it can be observed that the first principal component explains 21% of the total variance which is much more than the other principal components do. The other principal components except the last one explain 5-10% of the total variance. Taking these percentages into consideration, the first component is analyzed to draw insights about the relationship between geometry and the electromagnetic behavior.

The proportions of first (length of patch), second (width of patch), forth (height of substrate) and tenth (dielectric constant of substrate) features dominate the other coefficients. By looking the signs of them, it can be reached that width of patch, height of substrate and dielectric constant of substrate affect the principal component in a similar fashion (positively correlated) whereas, length of patch affects it in an opposite fashion meaning that while the length of patch increases the PC1 decreases. From this, it can be concluded that length of patch and the other three features affect the performance measure of S11 parameter in different directions. Other than that, it is likely that width of patch and height of substrate are important features for electromagnetic behavior since they have large coefficients in the principal component 1 (which explains the variability most and much more than the other features).

In the 2 output data, the rows represent the sample and the columns represent the 201 frequency points.

To proceed with the regression modeling for S11, two output data, real and imaginary output, are combined into one single output data by taking the square root of the sum of the squared real and imaginary data. In this single output, the magnitude of the output is calculated since the electromagnetic performance is quantified by the magnitude.

In [15]:

#Display the output data

Although the output data is represented in a single output data, the regression modeling is computationally hard since the output data is evaluated at 201 frequency points. To select a few frequency points that are important for regression, two methods are proposed in this section:

Method 1: Assigning weights to the each output and selecting the frequency points with highest weight/score

Method 2: Calculating the variance of each sample output, selecting the ones (samples) with highest variance and taking the sum of them

The main motivation behind these methods is to give importance to the low S11 magnitudes and consider the curves that has minimum magnitudes for selecting the critical frequency points. The reason is that the lower magnitudes mean better reflection performance, less signal loss around that frequency point which is desired in this study. On the other hand, the higher output values and curves like output 0, 3, 4, and 5 represent poor performances in terms of S11 parameter. Thus, these methods try to get rid of samples that have poor performance and to find critical frequency points by focusing on the sample and frequency pairs that show strong performance.

Method 1: Assigning weights to the each output and selecting the frequency points with highest weight/score

In this method, a weight of reciprocal of the magnitude value is given to each output. The reason underlying this weigthing method is to give more weight to the smaller output values. By giving more weight to the smaller output, the weight of frequency points, which is calculated by summing all the weights of output values at that frequency point, is aimed to be adjusted with respect to the desired output. Therefore, it is expected that the frequency points that have higher weights are the key frequencies since the weighting diminishes the effect of samples behave as undesired. Briefly, it's like rewarding the frequency points according to output values at that point.

Method 2: Calculating the variance of each sample output, selecting the ones (samples) with highest variance and taking the sum of them

The main idea of this method is to find the key frequency points by taking advantage of the variance of the samples. It can be seen on the graph which consists of output values of the first 6 designs that the samples performing poorly in terms of S11 parameter have less variance compared to the samples which have good performances at some frequencies. In order to avoid the samples that have poor performance and concentrate on the frequencies at which the other samples perform well, the variance of the sample output can be a useful parameter. The reason is that if the variance of the sample output is larger, then it probably performs in a desired fashion at certain frequency values. On the other hand, the bad performing samples have less variance as it can be seen on the plot of S11 magnitude for first 6 designs. After finding out the samples that have the largest variance, it is suggested to take the sum of the output values of those samples to find out which frequency points are critical.

Based on the regression model results, it is observed that the linear regression models for the real part of S11 is an effective model to cover the large proportion of the variance in the real part since the R² values are relatively high, around 0.80. In addition to R² values, the MSE values are fairly low (approximately 0.7 in average), indicating the regression models for real part fit well and have high accuracy. On the other hand, when the linear regression models for imaginary parts are examined, it is reached that the regression models perform poorly with very low R² values (varies between 0.0385-0.2635) and these models can not be interpreted as effective in the sense of capturing the relationship between the design parameters and the imaginary output of S11. Even though the MSE of these models are not that high, they are slightly higher than the MSE of the regression models for the real part. It can be concluded that there is something problematic in the imaginary regression models and these models can not explain the variance in imaginary output whereas, the real regression models indicate good performance in explaining the variance of the real part of S11 parameter and predicting it.

There are some patterns emerged after the regression results are obtained. Firstly, there are some frequency points such as 71, 155, and 88 that models perform better compared to the other frequencies. It can be said that the models perform better at certain frequencies where the data and the model align well. Based on this outcome, it is achieved that the first method proposed performs slightly better than the second method in identifying the key frequencies since all of the frequencies that models have high performance are found with Method 1. The second obvious pattern is the better prediction of the real part of the output and the poor prediction of the imaginary part of the output. The linear regression models perform quite well in predicting the real part of the output. This means that the design parameters, geometric parameters have strong linear relationship with the antenna's reflection performance. However, the performance of the models for the imaginary part is consistenly very weak. This result refers that the relationship between the design parameters and the imaginary output is not linear. This relationship might be non-linear or more complex. It should be analyzed with other complex factors.

4.Model Performance and Interpretability¶

The aim of the PCA is dimensionality reduction by identifying the principal components that are generated using the given features. To identify principal components, it benefits from the geometrical operations and find outs the principal components that explains most of the variance in the data. In this study, using PCA the number of features, in other words, design space is reduced to 8 features while losing very little variance information. Even though it helped to achieve more simple design space that can be interpreted and managed easier, the change and its performance is discussable since only 3 features out of 11 features are reduced. In practical sense, it can be expected to reduce to design space more by using PCA, for instance to 4-5 components. Depending on the application and analysis, the simplification can be preferred but in some cases, this simplification can be evaluated as insufficient considering the lost variance information. When it comes to the limitations of PCA, it might make it harder to determine the effect of each feature, in this case each geometry parameter, on the S11 parameter of the antenna since it introduces new components with existing features although it reduces the number of components. To improve the model's performance, PCA can be used as an additional tool with other models and methods for explaining more complex and non-linear models.

The regression models try to establish a relationship between the input parameters (features) and the output measures based on given data. Basically, it fits a model to the data. As it is observed in this study, the regression models can be a very powerful method to predict the output with high accuracy. However, sometimes when the relationship is non-linear or more complex, it might end up with poor performance models as in the prediction models of the imaginary part. The limitation of these models is the linearity assumption. This assumption might arise problems in capturing complex and non-linear relationships such as the antenna and the design parameters. To improve these models in complex systems, non-linear regression models can be employed.

5.Conclusion¶

To wrap up, the PCA is used to reduce the dimensonality of the design space where the features are the geometric parameters of the antenna, and regression models are used to capture relationship between design parameters of the antenna and its reflection performance in this study. By applying PCA to the input data, more simplifed design space with 8 principal components is achieved and an inference about the geometric parameters and the electromagnetic behavior is made. On the regression models side, firstly, two methods are suggested to determine the key frequency points to alleviate the computational load by interpreting the output graph of the samples. After the key frequency points are determined with each method, the linear regression models are constructed using the key frequency points and their performances are assessed. At the end, the limitations and results about the study are presented and some improvements are suggested accordingly.
